# Chess Skill Estimation Using a TrueSkill-Style Bayesian Model

## Project Overview

This project investigates skill estimation in chess using a probabilistic graphical model. We implement a TrueSkill-style latent variable model in PyMC to infer player skill levels from historical chess games and predict future match outcomes.

The project focuses on Bayesian inference, latent variables, and probabilistic prediction.

## Team Members

* Shea Thomopoulos
* Pragya Jhunjhunwala

## Our  Research Question

Can a Bayesian latent skill model accurately estimate player skill and predict the outcomes of future chess matches using historical game data?

## Dataset

We used a publicly available chess game data from Lichess.

The raw data should be placed in:

data/raw/

Processed datasets will be stored in:

data/processed/

## Environment Setup

Create a virtual environment:

```bash
python -m venv .venv
```

To activate it:

Mac/Linux:

```bash
source .venv/bin/activate
```

Windows:

```bash
.venv\Scripts\activate
```

To Install dependencies:

```bash
pip install -r requirements.txt
```

## Running the Project

Data preprocessing:

```bash
python src/data_processing.py
```

Train the model:

```bash
python src/model.py
```

Evaluate predictions:

```bash
python src/evaluate.py
```

## Technologies we used:

* Python
* PyMC
* NumPy
* Pandas
* ArviZ
* Matplotlib
* Jupyter Notebook

